      "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deroplatys_lobata",
      "content": {
        "common_name": "Dead Leaf Mantis",
        "scientific_name": "Deroplatys lobata",
        "description": "The Dead Leaf Mantis is a remarkable species from Southeast Asia that has evolved to perfectly mimic dead, dried leaves. Native to Thailand, Java, Borneo, Indonesia, Sumatra, and the Malay Peninsula, these mantids inhabit tropical rainforest floors where they blend seamlessly among fallen foliage. Their brown coloration ranges from dark gray to light mottled gray, often with a pinkish flush, and features a distinctive broad, ripped-looking prothorax that enhances their leaf-like appearance. Females grow to 65-70mm while males reach about 45mm in length.\n\nPeople are drawn to these mantids for their incredible camouflage abilities and unique defensive behaviors. When threatened, nymphs will 'play dead' by dropping to the ground with legs folded, while adults display striking wing patterns with eyespots and zebra-striped forelegs to startle predators. Their relatively calm temperament and fascinating appearance make them highly sought-after in the exotic pet trade, though their specific care requirements and breeding challenges place them in the intermediate difficulty category.",
        "care_guide": {
          "temperature_f": "75-86 (day), 64-75 (night)",
          "humidity_percent": "50-80",
          "enclosure_type": "Well-ventilated glass terrarium or mesh enclosure with plenty of branches and twigs",
          "enclosure_size": "Minimum 3x mantis length in height, 2x in width (9 inches tall for adult female)",
          "substrate": "Paper towel with optional sphagnum moss for humidity retention",
          "diet": "Nymphs: fruit flies (D. melanogaster, then D. hydei). Adults: flying insects preferred - moths, blue bottle flies, house flies. Feed every 2-3 days, amount they'll eat in one sitting",
          "water": "Mist enclosure walls daily for drinking droplets and humidity maintenance",
          "lifespan": "Up to 1 year with proper care",
          "difficulty": "Intermediate",
          "special_notes": "Prone to molting difficulties due to large prothorax shield - maintain proper humidity during molts. Can be kept communally until L3-L4 with adequate food. Males mature faster (L7) than females (L9), making breeding timing challenging. Remove smooth surfaces as they need rough gripping points for molting"
        },
        "fun_facts": [
          "Females guard their egg cases by sitting on them until hatching - rare parental care behavior in mantids",
          "Can slightly adjust their coloration over molts to better match surrounding leaf litter",
          "Their 'death feigning' defense can last several minutes, remaining motionless even when touched"
        ],
        "buying_tips": "Look for L3-L4 nymphs rather than adults for easier acclimation. Ensure the seller provides proper ventilation during shipping. Check for intact limbs and active feeding response before purchasing.",
        "faqs": [
          {
            "q": "Can Dead Leaf Mantises be kept together?",
            "a": "Young nymphs (L1-L3) can be housed communally with adequate space and food, but should be separated by L4 to prevent cannibalism"
          },
          {
            "q": "Why did my mantis drop to the ground and stop moving?",
            "a": "This is their natural 'playing dead' defense behavior when startled - they'll resume normal activity after feeling safe"
          },
          {
            "q": "What's the biggest challenge in keeping this species?",
            "a": "Molting can be difficult due to their large shield, requiring consistent humidity and proper grip surfaces"
          },
          {
            "q": "How often should I feed my Dead Leaf Mantis?",
            "a": "Feed every 2-3 days, offering as much as they'll eat in one sitting. They'll stop eating 1-2 days before molting"
          }
        ],
        "seo_title": "Dead Leaf Mantis Care Guide & Where to Buy",
        "seo_description": "Complete Deroplatys lobata care guide covering temperature (75-86\u00b0F), humidity (50-80%), diet, and housing for this incredible leaf-mimicking mantis",
