      "slug": "devils-flower-mantis",
      "common_name": "Devils Flower Mantis",
      "scientific_name": "Idolomantis diabolica",
      "category": "Mantis",
      "category_slug": "mantis",
      "price_range": "85-125",
      "primary_use": "Pet",
      "photo_url": "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/12782841/large.jpg",
      "photo_attribution": "(c) James, some rights reserved (CC BY)",
      "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Idolomantis",
      "content": {
        "common_name": "Devils Flower Mantis",
        "scientific_name": "Idolomantis diabolica",
        "description": "The Devils Flower Mantis is one of the most spectacular and sought-after mantis species in the hobby, earning the nickname \"King of all mantids.\" Native to East Africa (particularly Tanzania, Kenya, and Ethiopia), these giants grow to impressive sizes - females reaching up to 5 inches and males around 4 inches. What truly sets them apart is their absolutely stunning threat display, revealing vibrant red, white, blue, and black markings on their raptorial legs when startled. Adults feature beautiful white and green coloration with an impressive shield-like pronotum on their back. Despite their intimidating appearance and name, they're actually quite skittish and nervous creatures that prefer to avoid confrontation. Their spectacular appearance, combined with their challenging care requirements and high price point ($85-125), makes them a true trophy species for experienced mantis keepers looking for the ultimate display animal.",
        "care_guide": {
          "temperature_f": "85-104\u00b0F (ideal 95\u00b0F), nighttime drop to 68-77\u00b0F",
          "humidity_percent": "40-60% (higher 70-90% at sub-adult stage for molting)",
          "enclosure_type": "Full mesh enclosure required - cannot climb smooth surfaces. Needs excellent ventilation with heat lamp positioned above",
          "enclosure_size": "Minimum 16\"H x 12\"W x 12\"D for adults, height 3x mantis length",
          "substrate": "Paper towels recommended - no loose substrate that prevents them from righting themselves if they fall",
          "diet": "FLYING PREY ONLY - L1-L2: D. melanogaster fruit flies, L2-L3: D. hydei fruit flies, L4-L5: house flies, L6-Adult: blue bottle flies. Will NOT chase prey - only catches flying insects. Feed daily or every other day",
          "water": "Mist once daily for drinking, ensure good ventilation so water evaporates by morning. Use distilled/RO water only",
          "lifespan": "12 months with proper care",
          "difficulty": "Advanced",
          "special_notes": "Extremely stress-prone - minimize handling. Cannot climb glass/plastic. Molting issues are the #1 killer. Never feed crickets - disrupts ootheca production. Requires consistent high heat and flying prey availability"
        },
        "fun_facts": [
          "Newborn nymphs are shiny black to mimic ants for protection, then turn beige/brown before their stunning adult colors emerge",
          "Can decapitate prey with a single strike using their exceptionally powerful raptorial forelegs",
          "Males have distinctive feather-shaped antennae while females have regular antennae"
        ],
        "buying_tips": "Start with easier species first (Ghost, Orchid, then Violin mantis) to build experience with flying prey and high temperatures. Buy young nymphs (L1-L3) rather than adults for better acclimation. Ensure you have a reliable supply of fruit flies and blue bottle flies before purchasing.",
        "faqs": [
          {
            "q": "Why won't my Devils Flower Mantis eat crickets?",
            "a": "This species exclusively hunts flying prey and will ignore crawling insects unless desperately hungry. They're ambush predators that snatch flies from mid-air."
          },
          {
            "q": "Do they really need such high temperatures?",
            "a": "Yes, 85-95\u00b0F is essential. They'll become sluggish, stop eating, or enter dormancy (aestivation) if kept too cool."
          },
          {
            "q": "Can I keep multiple together?",
            "a": "While less cannibalistic than other species, it's risky. They may grab the same fly and injure each other, or eat smaller individuals."
          },
          {
            "q": "Why is this species so expensive and hard to find?",
            "a": "High mortality rates, specific care requirements, and difficulty breeding make captive-bred specimens rare and valuable."
          }
        ],
        "seo_title": "Devils Flower Mantis Care Guide & Where to Buy",
        "seo_description": "Complete guide to keeping Devils Flower Mantis (Idolomantis diabolica). Learn temperature, humidity, diet requirements & why this $85-125 species needs experienced keepers.",
