        ],
        "buying_tips": "Look for active nymphs at L3-L4 stage for easiest care and longest time to enjoy them. Avoid adults unless you're experienced with breeding. Check that the mantis has all legs intact and moves normally - missing limbs indicate poor molting conditions.",
        "faqs": [
          {
            "q": "Can I keep multiple Giant Asian Mantises together?",
            "a": "No, they're highly cannibalistic and should be housed individually after L3-L4 stage. Even well-fed individuals will attack cage mates."
          },
          {
            "q": "Why is my mantis hanging upside down and not eating?",
            "a": "It's preparing to molt. Stop feeding and maintain proper humidity. Don't disturb it for 24 hours after molting while the new exoskeleton hardens."
          },
          {
            "q": "What's the difference between males and females?",
            "a": "Females are larger (4 inches vs 3 inches), bulkier, and have 6 abdominal segments. Males are slimmer with 8 segments and proportionally longer wings."
