          "lifespan": "12-18 months",
          "difficulty": "Intermediate",
          "special_notes": "Cannot be housed communally\u2014keep separately. Watch for overfeeding (round abdomen means stop feeding for a few days). Females can be aggressive toward males during breeding. Provide branches or sticks for climbing and molting support. Good ventilation is essential to prevent mold"
        },
        "fun_facts": [
          "This species is sometimes called 'Stinker' in the trade due to defensive secretions when threatened",
          "They reach adulthood after approximately 9 molts (L10 stage)",
          "Females can lay oothecae containing over 200 eggs that hatch in 4-6 weeks"
        ],
        "buying_tips": "Look for L3-L5 nymphs which are easier to raise than tiny L1-L2 babies. Ensure the seller provides proper ventilation during shipping. Ask about the mantis's current diet stage to know what feeders to have ready.",
        "faqs": [
          {
            "q": "Can Giant Shield Mantises be kept together?",
            "a": "No, they cannot be housed communally and will cannibalize each other if kept together. Always house them individually."
          },
          {
            "q": "Why is proper humidity so important for this species?",
            "a": "As tropical mantises from Thailand, they cannot tolerate dry conditions like desert species can. Low humidity leads to molting problems and health issues."
          },
          {
            "q": "How often should I feed my Giant Shield Mantis?",
            "a": "Feed twice weekly, but watch their abdomen\u2014if it looks very round, skip feeding for a few days to prevent overfeeding which shortens lifespan."
          },
          {
            "q": "What's the best starter size to buy?",
            "a": "L3-L5 nymphs are ideal\u2014they're past the fragile early stages but still have plenty of growing to do, giving you the full experience of raising them."
          }
        ],
