    {
      "slug": "cobalt-blue-tarantula",
      "common_name": "Cobalt Blue Tarantula",
      "scientific_name": "Cyriopagopus lividus",
      "category": "Tarantula",
      "category_slug": "tarantula",
      "price_range": "40-80",
      "primary_use": "Pet",
      "photo_url": "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/96537492/large.jpg",
      "photo_attribution": "(c) Sarka Masova, some rights reserved (CC BY)",
      "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cobalt_blue_tarantula",
      "content": {
        "common_name": "Cobalt Blue Tarantula",
        "scientific_name": "Cyriopagopus lividus",
        "description": "The Cobalt Blue Tarantula is one of the most visually striking species in the hobby, famous for its electric blue iridescent legs that seem to glow under light. Native to the rainforests of Myanmar and Thailand, these fossorial (burrowing) tarantulas spend most of their time underground in elaborate tunnel systems. Despite their stunning beauty, they're known for being one of the most defensive and unpredictable tarantulas in the hobby, with lightning-fast movements and a willingness to bite when threatened.\n\nPeople are drawn to this species for its incredible cobalt blue coloration, which develops as they mature from brownish juveniles into vibrant blue adults. However, this is truly a \"look but don't touch\" pet \u2013 their aggressive nature, potent venom (causing severe pain and muscle cramps), and tendency to bolt make them suitable only for experienced keepers. Sexual dimorphism is pronounced in this species: males turn brown at maturity and live only 5-6 years, while females retain their blue coloration and can live 15-18 years.\n\nIf you're considering a Cobalt Blue, understand that you're getting a beautiful display animal that will rarely be visible, as they're obligate burrowers who typically only emerge at night. Their defensive behavior combined with medically significant venom makes them a challenging species that demands respect and proper husbandry.",
        "care_guide": {
          "temperature_f": "75-85",
          "humidity_percent": "75-85",
          "enclosure_type": "Terrestrial setup with very deep substrate for burrowing",
          "enclosure_size": "10-15 gallon tank minimum for adults; height matters less than floor space and substrate depth",
          "substrate": "At least 6 inches of moisture-retaining substrate like coconut fiber, peat moss, or soil mix",
          "diet": "Juveniles: 2 small crickets every 7-10 days. Adults: 5-6 large crickets or 1 large dubia roach every 3-4 weeks. Wait 7+ days after molting before feeding",
          "water": "Shallow water dish required; keep substrate damp but not waterlogged. Overflow water dish occasionally to maintain corner moisture",
          "lifespan": "Females: 15-18 years, Males: 5-6 years",
          "difficulty": "Advanced",
          "special_notes": "Extremely defensive with medically significant venom. Never handle. Provide starter burrow but they'll dig their own. Keep one corner slightly damp. Fast escape artist - secure lid essential. Will slap ground and show threat pose before biting"
        },
        "fun_facts": [
          "Males turn brown at maturity while females stay blue, making this one of the most sexually dimorphic tarantula species",
          "Their scientific name 'lividus' means 'bluish' or 'bruised' in Latin, perfectly describing their stunning coloration",
          "Despite being called 'Cobalt Blue,' juveniles start life brown and gradually develop their blue coloration with each molt"
        ],
        "buying_tips": "Buy from reputable breeders who can provide captive-bred specimens - wild-caught are more defensive and stressed. Look for well-started juveniles (1-2 inches) rather than tiny slings, as they're hardier. Avoid sellers who claim these make good beginner tarantulas or downplay their defensive nature.",
        "faqs": [
          {
            "q": "Can I handle my Cobalt Blue Tarantula?",
            "a": "No, this species should never be handled. They're extremely fast, defensive, and have medically significant venom that causes severe pain and muscle cramping."
          },
          {
            "q": "Why can't I see my tarantula?",
            "a": "This is normal! Cobalt Blues are obligate burrowers who spend 99% of their time underground. You might see them at their burrow entrance at night or when hunting."
          },
          {
            "q": "Is the bite dangerous?",
            "a": "While not typically life-threatening, their venom causes extreme pain, muscle spasms, and flu-like symptoms. Anyone allergic to bee stings should be especially cautious."
          },
          {
            "q": "Why is my male turning brown?",
            "a": "This is natural sexual dimorphism. Males lose their blue coloration when they reach maturity, while females stay blue throughout their lives."
          }
        ],
        "seo_title": "Cobalt Blue Tarantula Care Guide & Where to Buy",
        "seo_description": "Complete Cobalt Blue Tarantula (Cyriopagopus lividus) care guide. Learn proper setup, feeding, and why this stunning but defensive species needs experienced keepers.",
        "related_species": [
          "Singapore Blue Tarantula",
          "Cobalt Blue Baboon Spider",
          "Thai Black Tarantula"
        ],
        "sources_consulted": [
          "The Tarantula Collective care sheet with 75-85\u00b0F temps and 75-85% humidity",
          "Multiple sources confirming 6+ inches substrate depth requirement",
          "Consensus on advanced difficulty level due to defensive nature and venom potency"
        ]
      },
