    {
      "slug": "mexican-red-knee-tarantula",
      "common_name": "Mexican Red Knee Tarantula",
      "scientific_name": "Brachypelma hamorii",
      "category": "Tarantula",
      "category_slug": "tarantula",
      "price_range": "50-150",
      "primary_use": "Pet",
      "photo_url": "https://inaturalist-open-data.s3.amazonaws.com/photos/4016251/large.JPG",
      "photo_attribution": "(c) Alan Rockefeller, some rights reserved (CC BY), uploaded by Alan Rockefeller",
      "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brachypelma_hamorii",
      "content": {
        "common_name": "Mexican Red Knee Tarantula",
        "scientific_name": "Brachypelma hamorii",
        "description": "The Mexican Red Knee Tarantula is arguably the most iconic tarantula in the pet trade, recognized for its striking black body with vibrant orange-red patches on its leg segments (the \"knees\"). Native to the scrublands and dry forests of western Mexico, this species has become a hobbyist favorite thanks to its docile nature, impressive size (5-6 inch leg span), and remarkable longevity. Featured in movies like Indiana Jones and countless documentaries, these tarantulas have introduced more people to arachnid keeping than perhaps any other species.\n\nDespite their intimidating appearance, Mexican Red Knees are known for their calm temperament and tolerance of occasional handling, though they can be skittish and will flick urticating hairs when startled. What makes them particularly appealing to buyers is their combination of beauty, hardiness, and beginner-friendly care requirements. They spend much of their time visible in their enclosures rather than hiding, making them excellent display animals that can become treasured family pets for decades.\n\nAs a CITES-protected species due to past overcollection, it's crucial to purchase captive-bred specimens from reputable dealers. These long-lived tarantulas are an investment in a pet that, especially for females, may outlive their owners with proper care. Their slow growth rate means patience is required, but watching them develop from tiny spiderlings into impressive adults is part of the rewarding experience of keeping this classic species.",
        "care_guide": {
          "temperature_f": "70-80",
          "humidity_percent": "50-70",
          "enclosure_type": "Terrestrial setup with good ventilation and secure lid",
